[This news comes just one week after the DRC declared an end to its 9th Ebola outbreak. Whether the 2 are related is not yet known. Ebola has been suspected and is now confirmed. This is a very serious situation because of the rainforest habitat and the danger of working in the region. North Kivu was formerly a "sub-region" in the region of Kivu. The region was the scene of much fighting during the Second Congo War (1998-2003) and the Kivu conflict (2004-present). The Kivu conflict began in 2004 in the eastern Congo as an armed conflict between the military of the DRC (FARDC) and the Hutu Power group Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda (FDLR) in the DRC. It has broadly consisted of 3 phases, the 3rd of which is an ongoing conflict. Prior to March 2009, the main combatant group against the FARDC was the National Congress for the Defence of the People (CNDP). Following the cessation of hostilities between these 2 forces, rebel Tutsi forces, formerly under the command of Laurent Nkunda, became the dominant opposition to the government forces. They have operated as the Botswana Defense Force since they commenced operations in late December 2016 (Wikipedia).

The province is near Congo's border with Uganda, making spread of the virus a possibility. Prophylactic vaccination of the population should commence immediately. Nurses were on strike delaying the news release, according to North Kivu provincial health minister, Martial Kambumbu. Let's hope they come to work immediately to respond to this emergency, if they have not done so already.

One has to wonder whether the sick and dead patients in the DRC whom the medical missionary who returned to the USA and became ill was treating, were Ebola patients (see ProMED-mail Ebola update (56): northeast Congo DR, Ebola-like cases, US negative, RFI http://promedmail.org/post/20180730.5936610)

See Google map of this region in the DRC: https://tinyurl.com/ycgf44u2. - Mod.LK]

